{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ae0b434-aab3-4a13-8eb4-0ff6d8790ebe","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current repository. Here's the general guidance:\n\n**On macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** – run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n2. **Check for macOS crash reports** – look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n3. **Use `/cores/`** – macOS writes core dumps to `/cores/core.<pid>` (ensure the directory exists and is writable: `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`).\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`** – open the dump with:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n5. **Check `kern.corefile` sysctl** – verify the core dump path:\n   ```\n   sysctl kern.corefile\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** On Apple Silicon (arm64), SIP may prevent core dumps for some processes. You may need to partially disable SIP or use `lldb` to attach live instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ba9676b6-0f08-4087-bf75-e50c3fedccbc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't have relevant documentation about this topic. Let me answer from general knowledge about macOS crash dumps and NativeAOT.","outputTokens":323,"requestId":"C3C2:2EAB99:1C00F5F:1FA38FC:6A07C310"},"id":"f46064f7-787f-4a8a-b539-45bff746fd89","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:32.132Z","parentId":"6ee4e01e-259d-4ce4-a177-9c38b59d2019"}
